⊕meta⊕
name = "convert-script-to-sky-workflow"
description = "Read an existing shell script, Makefile target, or cron line and author an equivalent .sky workflow, then lint-loop and dry-run it."
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 3
⊕⊕

§read§
bash_file = "./read.sh"
§§

§author§
model = "sonnet"
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
depends_on = ["read"]
trigger_rule = "all_success"
§§

∆author∆
You convert an existing automation script into a Skylence `.sky` workflow.

Source file path: {{source}}
Target file to write: {{dir}}/{{name}}.sky

The source contents were captured by the upstream `read` node and are also in the env var $SKY_OUTPUT_READ. Read the source from that env var, or re-read the file at {{source}} directly with your tools — either is fine.

Author one `.sky` file at {{dir}}/{{name}}.sky following the sky-workflow-authoring skill. Mapping rules (best-effort, translate faithfully):

- A plain shell script body maps to a single `bash` node holding the commands as one double-quoted string with \n between lines. Shell-quote every variable.
- A cron line (e.g. `0 6 * * *`) maps to `trigger.schedule.cron` in the meta block.
- A Makefile target maps its recipe lines to a `bash` node; drop the leading tab and Make-only prefixes.
- Environment variables the script reads go into the meta `secrets` array; reference them as ordinary `$NAME` in bash.
- The workflow `name` MUST equal {{name}} and equal the filename stem.
- Include exactly one trigger. If the source has no cron schedule, use `trigger.manual = true`.
- Add `output_style = "terse"`. If you add any Claude node, also set `max_budget_usd`.

Write the file. Do not run anything. Report the path you wrote and a one-line summary of how you mapped the source.
∆∆

§lint§
model = "sonnet"
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
depends_on = ["author"]
trigger_rule = "all_success"
loop.until.bash = "sky lint \"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NAME.sky\""
loop.max = 6
§§

∆lint∆
Run `sky lint` on the workflow you just authored and fix every error and warning until it exits 0.

Target file: {{dir}}/{{name}}.sky

Each loop pass:
1. Run: sky lint "{{dir}}/{{name}}.sky"
2. Read each reported code (e.g. SKY-WF-040, SKY-WF-055, SKY-WF-063) and the line it points at.
3. Edit the file to fix it. Common fixes: quote the RHS of every `when`; add any chain_from target to depends_on; declare every env token used in mcp_servers/http in the secrets array; add safety = "requires_permission" to any bash node using rm -r / rm -rf / rm -f; keep name equal to the filename stem.
4. Re-lint.

Stop when `sky lint` exits 0. Report the final lint output.
∆∆

§dryrun§
bash_file = "./dryrun.sh"
depends_on = ["lint"]
§§

※※
================================================================================
convert-script-to-sky-workflow
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Reads an existing shell script / Makefile target / cron line and authors an
equivalent .sky workflow, then lint-loops it clean and does a best-effort
dry-run.

HONESTY: the shell-to-bash-node translation is BEST-EFFORT. A working script
does not guarantee a working bash node (template vars, isolation, secrets,
exit-code semantics all differ). Always review the generated .sky before
trusting it in production.

DAG
---
  read ──▶ author ──▶ lint ──▶ dryrun

  read    bash; cat the source file, exit 1 if missing or empty
  author  claude/sonnet; map the source to {{dir}}/{{name}}.sky
  lint    claude/sonnet loop; `sky lint` until exit 0 (loop.max 6)
  dryrun  bash; `sky run <name> --dry-run`, best-effort (never fails the run)

RUN
---
  sky run convert-script-to-sky-workflow \
    --var dir=.sky/workflows \
    --var name=my-new-workflow \
    --var source=scripts/nightly-backup.sh

VARS
----
  dir     directory to write the new .sky into     -> $SKY_DIR
          (e.g. .sky/workflows)
  name    workflow name AND filename stem;          -> $SKY_NAME
          MUST be kebab-case (e.g. my-new-workflow)
  source  path to the script / Makefile / cron      -> $SKY_SOURCE
          line to convert (e.g. scripts/backup.sh)

NOTES
-----
- author/lint read the source via $SKY_OUTPUT_READ or by re-reading {{source}}.
- lint loops at most 6 times; if still dirty, inspect the file and the last
  lint output by hand.
- dryrun swallows failures (|| true) so a half-valid draft still surfaces
  output instead of failing the whole run.
- No destructive flags (no rm -r / rm -rf / rm -f), so no node needs
  safety = "requires_permission".
================================================================================
※※
